em to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":2,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":12,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William FitzRoger Gressenhall was born about 1094, in Huntingfield, Suffolk, England as the son of Roger FitzWimer de Gressenhall. He had at least 1 daughter with Aeliva."},"et":{"about 1094–":"umbes 1094–Surnud","1094–Male":"1094–Surnud","1135–1202":"1135–1202","1155–1209":"1155–1209","1080–1140":"1080–1140","about 1094":"umbes 1094","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1202":"1202","1135":"1135","1155":"1155","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","about 1155":"umbes 1155","1209":"1209","1094":"1094","England":"England","Huntingfield, Suffolk, England":"Huntingfield, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1094–":"noin 1094–Kuollut","1094–Male":"1094–Kuollut","1135–1202":"1135–1202","1155–1209":"1155–1209","1080–1140":"1080–1140","about 1094":"noin 1094","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1202":"1202","1135":"1135","1155":"1155","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","about 1155":"noin 1155","1209":"1209","1094":"1094","England":"England","Huntin